// Name: Custom Security Attribute Set on a User
// Description: Detects 'Update attribute values assigned to a user' events for Entra
//              custom security attributes. Attributes are used to drive Conditional
//              Access, app role assignments, and Defender policies ‚Äî modifying them
//              changes who can access what, silently.
// MITRE ATT&CK: T1098    (Account Manipulation),
//               T1556    (Modify Authentication Process)
// Data Source: AuditLogs (Entra ID directory audit)
// Platform:    Microsoft Sentinel / Log Analytics
// Time window: default workspace range
// Reference:   ./Custom-Security-Attribute-Set.md
// Context:     Custom security attributes are increasingly used in Entra for
//              filtering CA policies and ABAC. An attacker who can change a target's
//              attribute value effectively changes which CA policies apply ‚Äî a
//              subtle, audit-evading privilege escalation.
//
// Recommended actions on hits:
// - Verify the Actor is an authorized attribute definition / assignment admin
// - Check whether the attribute is used by any Conditional Access filter
// - If unauthorized, restore the previous value and investigate the Actor
//
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Extended context, background, tuning, and attribution
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
//
// # Custom Security Attribute Set on a User
//
// <sub>[‚Üê Back to KQL index](../README.md)</sub>
//
// > Source: [reprise99 / Sentinel-Queries ‚Äî Audit-CustomSecurityAttributeSet.kql](https://github.com/reprise99/Sentinel-Queries/blob/main/Azure%20Active%20Directory/Audit-CustomSecurityAttributeSet.kql) ¬∑ MIT License
//
// ## Why this hunt
//
// Custom Security Attributes (CSAs) were introduced in Entra ID to enable **attribute-based access control (ABAC)**. A growing number of organisations use them as:
//
// - Filters for **Conditional Access policies** (e.g., apply policy only to users with `Department=Finance`)
// - **Role assignment conditions** ‚Äî scope a role by attribute value
// - **Defender policy scoping** ‚Äî focus DLP or Insider Risk on tagged cohorts
// - **Application access** ‚Äî apps that read attributes via Graph to make authorization decisions
//
// Because CSAs are increasingly load-bearing for access decisions, they are **an attractive, low-noise persistence target**:
//
// - Changing a target user's `Clearance=Secret` to `Clearance=TopSecret` may silently bring them into scope of resources they shouldn't see
// - Removing a user from `RestrictedGroup=True` may exempt them from a CA policy that was blocking their access
// - An attacker who has the **Attribute Definition Administrator** role can do this without being a Global Admin ‚Äî lower-privilege pivot
//
// Most organisations have **no detective control** on CSA changes today. This hunt closes that gap.
//
// ## Expected output
//
// | Column | What it tells you |
// |---|---|
// | `TimeGenerated` | When the attribute was changed |
// | `Target` | UPN of the user whose attribute was modified |
// | `Attribute Set Name` | Which CSA set (e.g., `Engineering`, `Compliance`) |
// | `Attribute Name` | Which attribute within the set (e.g., `Clearance`) |
// | `Attribute Value` | New value |
// | `Actor` | UPN of the modifier |
//
// This is an awareness hunt ‚Äî most tenants will see zero or very few rows. If the tenant uses CSAs heavily, baseline the normal actors and alert on off-baseline changes.
//
// ## Tuning notes
//
// - **Low-volume, high-signal** ‚Äî output is typically small; review every row during initial rollout, then baseline
// - **No explicit time window** ‚Äî relies on workspace retention. For a scheduled rule, set `queryFrequency: 1d` and `queryPeriod: 1d`
// - **Attribute-level allow-list** ‚Äî if a specific attribute is known to change frequently (e.g., `LastTrainingDate`), exclude it in `| where ['Attribute Name'] !in (...)`
// - **Enrich with CA policy usage** ‚Äî if the attribute changed is used by a CA policy filter, escalate severity
// - **Pair with sign-in correlation** ‚Äî join the Target's `SigninLogs` for 24h after the change; look for access to newly-unlocked resources
//
// ## Recommended hardening
//
// 1. **Restrict Attribute Definition Administrator assignments** ‚Äî PIM + approval + MFA. Treat as Tier-1 privilege
// 2. **Use attribute sets as authorization boundaries** ‚Äî each attribute set should have distinct owners and reviewers
// 3. **Attribute change review workflow** ‚Äî require a ticket / change-management entry for every attribute change; reconcile against this hunt's output weekly
// 4. **Monitor CA policy filter expressions** ‚Äî quarterly review of which CA policies reference custom attributes, which values filter to what scope
// 5. **Avoid load-bearing sensitive decisions on mutable attributes** ‚Äî for top-critical decisions, use group membership + access reviews, which are harder to modify silently
//
// ## References
//
// - [MITRE ATT&CK T1098 ‚Äî Account Manipulation](https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1098/)
// - [Microsoft Learn: Custom security attributes overview](https://learn.microsoft.com/entra/fundamentals/custom-security-attributes-overview)
// - [Microsoft Learn: ABAC conditions in Entra role assignments](https://learn.microsoft.com/entra/identity/role-based-access-control/conditions-overview)

AuditLogs
| where OperationName == "Update attribute values assigned to a user"
| extend x = tostring(parse_json(tostring(TargetResources[0].modifiedProperties))[0].displayName)
| extend ["Attribute Value"] = tostring(parse_json(tostring(parse_json(tostring(TargetResources[0].modifiedProperties))[0].newValue))[0])
| extend Target = tostring(TargetResources[0].userPrincipalName)
| extend Actor = tostring(parse_json(tostring(InitiatedBy.user)).userPrincipalName)
| parse x with * '.' ['Attribute Set Name'] "_" *
| extend ["Attribute Name"]=split(x, "_")[1]
| project
    TimeGenerated,
    OperationName,
    Target,
    ['Attribute Set Name'],
    ['Attribute Name'],
    ['Attribute Value'],
    Actor
